        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Restaurant Fire Safety Requirements in Reno, NV: What Every Operator Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">Reno's casino hotel restaurants, the Midtown arts and dining district, and growing food service operations at the Tahoe-Reno Industrial Center all face Nevada Fire Code kitchen suppression requirements. Casino food and beverage operations spanning multiple kitchen facilities create complex multi-system compliance obligations. Here's what Reno restaurant and casino food service operators need to know.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">NFPA 96 Kitchen Suppression Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">All commercial cooking operations in Reno producing grease-laden vapors must install and maintain an automatic wet chemical fire suppression system under NFPA 96. This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias. Reno's restaurant compliance is anchored by casino hotel properties along Virginia Street — each with multiple restaurant outlets, buffet operations, and bar kitchens requiring separate semi-annual NFPA 96 inspections. Midtown's independent restaurant scene and the Riverwalk District's dining corridor also generate significant kitchen suppression compliance demand.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Semi-Annual Inspection Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires kitchen suppression systems to be inspected and serviced semi-annually — twice per year — by a licensed contractor. Records must be maintained on-site and available for Reno Fire Department inspection. Semi-annual means every six months from the last inspection date, not twice per calendar year.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Hood Cleaning Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires hood cleaning at intervals based on cooking volume: quarterly for high-volume operations (solid fuel cooking, charbroiling, wok cooking, high-volume fryers), semi-annually for moderate volume, annually for low-volume like pizza ovens. Hood cleaning records must be maintained on-site.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Class K Fire Extinguisher</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A Class K extinguisher must be within 30 feet of all cooking surfaces producing grease-laden vapors. Class K units are specifically designed for cooking oil fires — standard ABC dry chemical is not an adequate substitute. Class K units require annual inspection alongside other extinguishers.</p>
