        <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Our Reno casino has multiple restaurant and buffet kitchens. How does NFPA 96 apply to each operation?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Each commercial cooking operation with a hood-and-duct system requires its own semi-annual NFPA 96 inspection. A casino hotel with a buffet, three restaurants, a sports bar kitchen, and room service prep may have six or more separate systems. Each must be independently inspected and documented. The Reno Fire Department cites each non-compliant system separately.</p></div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does every Reno restaurant need a kitchen fire suppression system?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. All commercial cooking operations in Reno producing grease-laden vapors must have an automatic wet chemical suppression system under NFPA 96 and the Nevada Fire Code (IFC-based). This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often does kitchen fire suppression need to be inspected in Reno?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">NFPA 96 requires semi-annual inspection — twice per year — for all commercial kitchen suppression systems. Inspection must be performed by a licensed contractor and documented. The Reno Fire Department enforces this requirement.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does kitchen suppression inspection cost in Reno?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">$175–$375 per system per system. Budget for two inspections annually.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What is the most common kitchen fire safety violation in Reno?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Common violations in Reno include: Overdue semi-annual suppression in casino food service — high-volume buffet and restaurant kitchens require rigorous scheduling; Staggered inspection dates across multiple casino kitchen systems creating rolling compliance gaps.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who licenses kitchen suppression contractors in NV?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The Nevada State Fire Marshal Division ((775) 684-7501) licenses fire protection contractors statewide. Verify your suppression contractor holds current NV credentials before scheduling service.</p></div></div>
